# Reswell — Cursor AI rules

## Stack
- Next.js App Router (`app/`), React 19, TypeScript (`strict`), Tailwind CSS, path alias `@/*`.
- UI: Radix primitives, `class-variance-authority`, `tailwind-merge`, `lucide-react`.
- Data/auth: Supabase (`@supabase/ssr`, `@supabase/supabase-js`). Payments: Stripe. Other integrations as present in `lib/` and `app/api/`.

## General
- Change only what the task requires. No drive-by refactors or unrelated edits.
- Before adding code, read nearby files and match naming, types, imports, and component patterns.
- Prefer extending existing helpers and components over duplicating logic.
- Do not add README/markdown docs unless asked.

## TypeScript & React
- Use explicit types at boundaries (API handlers, `fetch` JSON, props). Avoid `any`; use `unknown` and narrow.
- Prefer server components by default; add `"use client"` only when hooks, browser APIs, or client-only libs require it.
- Colocate feature UI with its route or a nearby `components` folder following existing layout.

## Next.js
- Use App Router conventions: `layout.tsx`, `page.tsx`, `route.ts`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx` as appropriate.
- API routes: validate input (e.g. Zod), return appropriate HTTP status codes, avoid leaking internal errors in production responses.

## Styling
- Use Tailwind utilities and existing design tokens/patterns. Keep spacing, typography, and colors consistent with adjacent UI.

## Security & env
- Never commit secrets. Use `.env.example` for new env vars (placeholders only). Server-only keys stay in server code / Route Handlers.

## Testing & quality
- After substantive edits, run `npm run lint` and fix new issues you introduce.
